WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.900
 So now we're gonna talk about how you use JavaScript

00:00:02.900 --> 00:00:05.300
 in a browser, and as I said before,

00:00:05.300 --> 00:00:07.620
 this is just only one of the possible ways

00:00:07.620 --> 00:00:09.980
 that you might use Java, but this is pretty much

00:00:09.980 --> 00:00:12.860
 what we'd call vanilla Java, or basic Java,

00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:15.780
 or Java without view, or Java without jQuery,

00:00:15.780 --> 00:00:17.060
 or Java without node.

00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:21.500
 This was the original JavaScript purpose, right?

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:25.660
 It was to be in the browser, augment HTML.

00:00:25.660 --> 00:00:30.440
 So here we have a happy little bit of HTML.

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:32.060
 We've got some HTML, you've got a body,

00:00:32.060 --> 00:00:34.860
 you've got a paragraph tag, and we've got this script tag.

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:38.860
 So the script tag says we're moving out of HTML as syntax,

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:42.300
 and we are then writing some JavaScript code.

00:00:42.300 --> 00:00:44.840
 And we are talking to the document.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:48.740
 Document, the DOM, is in a sense that part of your browser

00:00:48.740 --> 00:00:51.500
 that's like the pixels that you're seeing.

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:54.280
 And so this JavaScript code can write

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:55.840
 to what you're seeing on the screen

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:59.620
 by going through this variable called document.

00:00:59.620 --> 00:01:03.380
 Document.write writes onto the screen.

00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:05.520
 And so if you take a look at this code,

00:01:05.520 --> 00:01:09.900
 it's coming down, the title out comes to the body,

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:12.620
 the paragraph comes out, then it drops into JavaScript,

00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:14.620
 and then this little string gets written out,

00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:16.140
 then it goes back in.

00:01:16.140 --> 00:01:18.480
 The no script tag is in case there's no JavaScript,

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:20.180
 which is really rare these days,

00:01:20.180 --> 00:01:21.880
 and then the paragraph comes out.

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:26.180
 So the point is that this has created a three line web page,

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:29.620
 the first and the third line come from HTML,

00:01:29.620 --> 00:01:31.940
 and the second line comes from JavaScript.

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:35.300
 Not that this is a particularly useful example.

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:39.780
 It just points out that JavaScript has access

00:01:39.780 --> 00:01:42.820
 to the screen when it's running inside of a web page.

00:01:42.820 --> 00:01:45.900
 That's powerful, and we're gonna drive a truck

00:01:45.900 --> 00:01:47.320
 through all that.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:48.940
 So whenever I learn a new programming language,

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:52.520
 the first thing I gotta do is print a debug statement.

00:01:52.520 --> 00:01:55.660
 And the debug statement is called alert,

00:01:55.660 --> 00:01:57.900
 and you say alert, you put a string in it,

00:01:57.900 --> 00:02:00.500
 and it stops, it stops the program,

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:02.920
 and you have to press okay, then it continues on.

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:05.140
 So that way I'm like, did that code run or not?

00:02:05.140 --> 00:02:06.980
 And I just put a little alert hello world in there,

00:02:06.980 --> 00:02:08.420
 and then poof, up it goes.

00:02:08.420 --> 00:02:10.400
 And then just pops up a little dialogue,

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:12.900
 and you press okay, and it continues.

00:02:12.900 --> 00:02:14.060
 So that's really quite nice.

00:02:14.060 --> 00:02:17.140
 And so here's a little example of that,

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:21.920
 where we're cruising along, the paragraph is written out.

00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:23.200
 And one of the things that you'll notice

00:02:23.200 --> 00:02:26.860
 is that this alert box actually stops the JavaScript.

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:28.500
 So we switch into JavaScript.

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:31.340
 The browser is still parsing the page,

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:35.120
 and you'll see sometimes little spinner is still spinning.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:38.420
 So it stops, it puts up the alert dialogue box,

00:02:38.420 --> 00:02:41.580
 here I am, and waits until you press okay.

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:45.260
 And in a sense, your browser is paused at that point.

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:47.700
 'Cause literally, it doesn't know what you're gonna do,

00:02:47.700 --> 00:02:49.340
 and this JavaScript has every right

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:50.820
 to change every bit of this page,

00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:55.100
 'cause the JavaScript is in the page, using a document.

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:58.540
 So it pauses until you press okay,

00:02:58.540 --> 00:02:59.660
 and then it picks back up,

00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:01.820
 and then it will write hello world,

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:04.060
 and the second paragraph will come.

00:03:04.060 --> 00:03:06.620
 But alert, you just stick it in your JavaScript,

00:03:06.620 --> 00:03:09.340
 and whatever's happening, bang, it stops right there,

00:03:09.340 --> 00:03:10.960
 and everything stops.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:14.740
 And so that's a pretty cool thing.

00:03:14.740 --> 00:03:17.820
 And so it's a, you can't use it too much,

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:18.860
 you can't use it in a loop,

00:03:18.860 --> 00:03:20.360
 and if you do it too many times,

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:21.200
 your browser will be like,

00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:23.580
 "Why is this page throwing up so many alert boxes?"

00:03:23.580 --> 00:03:26.740
 But in a pinch, it's the simplest thing.

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:33.100
 So there's three ways to get JavaScript into your web page.

00:03:33.100 --> 00:03:34.660
 One is inlining the document,

00:03:34.660 --> 00:03:35.660
 and that's what I just showed you

00:03:35.660 --> 00:03:38.620
 with a da-da-da-da script, da-da-da-da slash script.

00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:41.020
 It can be, we've done, and we've done this before,

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:43.380
 it's part of an event in an HTML tag.

00:03:43.380 --> 00:03:45.780
 And we'll show you that, or you can put the JavaScript

00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:49.740
 in its own little file, usually ending in .js.

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:51.180
 So here's the second one.

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:55.100
 This is the one where we're putting in an onClick method.

00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:57.340
 And so we've been doing this, right?

00:03:57.340 --> 00:03:58.940
 We've been doing onClick methods,

00:03:58.940 --> 00:04:01.460
 where we'll have an href, and then onClick,

00:04:01.460 --> 00:04:02.340
 and then say something.

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:04.860
 And in this one, this part here in the middle,

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:06.500
 that is just JavaScript,

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:09.100
 and that's why it has semicolons to end each line.

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:11.780
 White space doesn't matter, this isn't Python.

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:14.340
 Don't need new lines, et cetera.

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:18.340
 So when we click on this Click Me button,

00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:20.220
 that is going to start running this code.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:23.980
 Now the page is already fully rendered,

00:04:23.980 --> 00:04:26.300
 and the Click Me button is waiting to be clicked.

00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:28.620
 And onClick, that's when a click happens,

00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:33.140
 event-driven programming, then it runs the alert, pauses.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:34.660
 Better change the color there.

00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:37.540
 It runs the alert.

00:04:37.540 --> 00:04:41.500
 Hmm, how come I can't get it to be yellow?

00:04:42.620 --> 00:04:43.460
 There it's yellow.

00:04:43.460 --> 00:04:49.180
 Clear it, go back up, and be yellow.

00:04:49.180 --> 00:04:50.500
 Thank you for being yellow.

00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:53.740
 So you click on it, it runs this JavaScript,

00:04:53.740 --> 00:04:56.180
 which runs the alert, which pops the box up.

00:04:56.180 --> 00:04:59.100
 Then you press the OK, and then it continues on this code.

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:04.100
 Now the return false is telling the anchor tag

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.740
 not to follow the link, right?

00:05:06.740 --> 00:05:08.340
 And so that basically says,

00:05:08.340 --> 00:05:12.100
 I, the onClick method, have processed this particular click.

00:05:12.100 --> 00:05:14.140
 And so that's what the return false does.

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:19.140
 So we are basically just have JavaScript

00:05:19.140 --> 00:05:21.460
 in the middle of a tag that's triggered

00:05:21.460 --> 00:05:22.820
 when an event happens.

00:05:22.820 --> 00:05:24.420
 So event-based programming.

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:29.020
 The other thing we can do is we can make this

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:30.900
 in a completely separate file.

00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:33.540
 So we're gonna have this file called script.js.

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:35.020
 Now it doesn't need a script tag

00:05:35.020 --> 00:05:37.660
 'cause it knows that it's JavaScript, so that's just code.

00:05:37.660 --> 00:05:38.740
 This happens to be one line

00:05:38.740 --> 00:05:41.140
 that's got a document.writeHelloWorld,

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:43.980
 and now we embed it with a script tag and a slash script,

00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:46.020
 but now we just say source equals script.

00:05:46.020 --> 00:05:48.180
 It pulls it in, it loads and runs

00:05:48.180 --> 00:05:50.380
 and parses that whole thing.

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:53.660
 And as a side effect, it writes out one paragraph,

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:55.620
 hello world, and the second paragraph.

00:05:55.620 --> 00:05:58.500
 And of course, usually this isn't doing work.

00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:00.940
 Usually this is defining a bunch of functions

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:02.340
 that we're going to use later.

00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:04.620
 And so usually this is script.js

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:06.780
 is a function, function, function, function,

00:06:06.780 --> 00:06:09.500
 so we're kind of loading a library of functions

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:10.460
 that we're gonna use later.

00:06:10.460 --> 00:06:12.140
 But I just put this document right

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:14.740
 so you can kind of see when it's happening

00:06:14.740 --> 00:06:16.900
 as the document is loading.

00:06:16.900 --> 00:06:20.660
 So in any programming language,

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:23.220
 we can make errors as a programmer, right?

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:25.300
 We can make syntax errors.

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:30.300
 The problem is when you're looking at a webpage

00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:33.500
 and in that webpage, there's a JavaScript syntax error.

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:36.620
 They decided a long time ago

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:40.340
 not to bother the poor user with a JavaScript syntax error

00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:42.180
 because really the person,

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:44.260
 unless you're writing it in the first place,

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:48.540
 the person looking at the screen of amazon.com

00:06:48.540 --> 00:06:53.540
 or drchuck.com, if I got a syntax error in drchuck.com,

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:56.540
 why tell you that there's a syntax error?

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:58.820
 So what it actually does is it just like,

00:06:58.820 --> 00:07:02.380
 well, I guess I'll stop running the JavaScript

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:03.460
 because it's got a problem,

00:07:03.460 --> 00:07:04.660
 but I'm not gonna tell the user,

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:07.580
 which means my page is broken and I don't even know that.

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:11.220
 So it stops and so syntax errors happen

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:13.860
 and it just stops the execution.

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:17.380
 So let's take a look at a little example here,

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:19.980
 a little example where we have two chunks of JavaScript.

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:21.620
 We come in, we got the first one

00:07:21.620 --> 00:07:25.580
 and this first one has a syntax error, okay?

00:07:25.580 --> 00:07:27.460
 And that means the alert's not gonna work.

00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:31.220
 Now what happens is it in effect ignores everything

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:32.380
 after that point.

00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:34.140
 If it's executing through a script file,

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:35.660
 it might be defining a bunch of functions.

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:38.940
 If it finds a syntax error a third of the way through,

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:40.220
 the other two thirds don't matter

00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:43.340
 because it has stopped parsing that file

00:07:43.340 --> 00:07:45.420
 until the end of the script tag.

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:46.840
 And then when it sees a new script tag,

00:07:46.840 --> 00:07:50.340
 hope springs eternal and it starts parsing it again.

00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:52.960
 And so that's why when this page runs,

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:57.860
 when this page runs, you see first paragraph,

00:07:57.860 --> 00:08:02.100
 this goes, blows up, which means it skips down to here,

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:04.580
 then you see two paragraph come out

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:06.340
 and then you see the alert second time.

00:08:06.340 --> 00:08:08.500
 You never see any of these alerts

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:11.860
 because that error is on the first line of the JavaScript,

00:08:11.860 --> 00:08:15.380
 which invalidates the rest of the JavaScript,

00:08:15.380 --> 00:08:18.260
 but until another script tag.

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:20.500
 And sometimes what you're doing,

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:22.980
 you're like including one library, another library,

00:08:22.980 --> 00:08:25.060
 and another library, and another library.

00:08:25.060 --> 00:08:26.620
 If you have a syntax error in that library

00:08:26.620 --> 00:08:27.700
 that you're including,

00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:30.940
 most of that library won't actually be activated, right?

00:08:30.940 --> 00:08:34.940
 And, but it doesn't mean if you have like five libraries

00:08:34.940 --> 00:08:36.540
 that you're loading with five script tags,

00:08:36.540 --> 00:08:38.380
 just 'cause the first library has a syntax error,

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:41.100
 it can still load the other four libraries.

00:08:41.100 --> 00:08:43.660
 But it's just, it pumps.

00:08:43.660 --> 00:08:46.540
 There could be hundreds of lines of code here

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:50.140
 and it all is for naught because it saw a syntax error

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:53.140
 and ignored the rest of it up to the end of that script tag.

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:57.660
 Now, the end user can't see the error.

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:00.060
 So when you're doing software development,

00:09:00.060 --> 00:09:01.820
 you gotta put in extra effort.

00:09:01.820 --> 00:09:04.340
 'Cause when you're like writing code and hitting refresh,

00:09:04.340 --> 00:09:05.780
 writing code and hitting refresh,

00:09:05.780 --> 00:09:08.820
 well, yeah, that's the user hitting the refresh

00:09:08.820 --> 00:09:10.860
 in the browser, but if you're writing JavaScript,

00:09:10.860 --> 00:09:12.540
 you wanna see what's wrong.

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:15.100
 And so we have places that we have to look

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:18.100
 to see if there are actually JavaScript errors in our code.

00:09:18.100 --> 00:09:20.060
 And once we start developing JavaScript,

00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:23.020
 I assure you that there will be errors in your code.

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:24.660
 There's always errors in my code.

00:09:24.660 --> 00:09:28.220
 And so all of these situations,

00:09:28.220 --> 00:09:32.020
 whether all these browsers, Firefox, Chrome, Safari,

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:34.260
 they all have some kind of a web developer console

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:35.700
 that you unlock.

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:38.620
 And then you can go, there's always one of these tabs

00:09:38.620 --> 00:09:39.660
 that says console.

00:09:39.660 --> 00:09:42.900
 And console is all the error messages that are coming up.

00:09:42.900 --> 00:09:45.660
 And so if you made that same bit of code

00:09:45.660 --> 00:09:47.580
 and you had the console turned on,

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:49.700
 you would see a happy little error

00:09:49.700 --> 00:09:53.260
 that says syntax error on line three of that file.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:56.060
 I mean, it would just run the okays later in the file,

00:09:56.060 --> 00:09:58.220
 but it will tell us that.

00:09:58.220 --> 00:10:01.980
 So you'll find that once you start developing JavaScript,

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:03.260
 you're making a big mistake

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:06.460
 if you don't have this little developer console open

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:10.060
 almost all the time, at least to the JavaScript console,

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:13.060
 because that's how you debug your JavaScript.

00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:15.980
 It'll literally just like silently, you're like,

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:17.860
 hmm, I changed something and nothing happened.

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:19.300
 I changed something and nothing happened.

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:20.260
 I'm going crazy.

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:21.860
 Well, look at the console.

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:23.020
 You changed something,

00:10:23.020 --> 00:10:24.780
 but there was a syntax error above it.

00:10:24.780 --> 00:10:26.620
 And so it didn't matter what you said after that.

00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:28.420
 It really ignores everything after that.

00:10:28.420 --> 00:10:30.820
 So that's why it's so important

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:33.940
 to have a debugger console doing all the time.

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:35.460
 Thankfully, all modern browsers

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:36.740
 have a good debugger console.

00:10:36.740 --> 00:10:38.780
 In the old days, Firefox was the only one

00:10:38.780 --> 00:10:40.340
 that had a thing called Firebug,

00:10:40.340 --> 00:10:42.980
 which was this console which had to install it and add it.

00:10:42.980 --> 00:10:46.260
 And it's a person wrote it as an open source project.

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:49.260
 And it got so popular that people just put it

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:51.380
 into the browsers rather than making you install it.

00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:53.100
 So it was pretty cool.

00:10:54.420 --> 00:10:56.060
 So back to debugging,

00:10:56.060 --> 00:10:59.980
 there is a function called console.log

00:10:59.980 --> 00:11:01.860
 and it allows you to log variables

00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:03.340
 and strings and whatever.

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:05.020
 And unlike the alert,

00:11:05.020 --> 00:11:06.940
 it just shows up in that console.

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:09.100
 That, that, that, that, that, that, that, that, that, that.

00:11:09.100 --> 00:11:10.780
 So you can put it inside of a loop.

00:11:10.780 --> 00:11:12.300
 You don't have to press okay.

00:11:12.300 --> 00:11:13.980
 It doesn't stop anything.

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:18.020
 It's really more of a debug print, right?

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:21.140
 And so in this particular example,

00:11:21.140 --> 00:11:22.660
 you know, it just runs.

00:11:22.660 --> 00:11:23.540
 It doesn't stop.

00:11:23.540 --> 00:11:24.820
 The alert stops everything.

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:27.980
 And so I use the alert like, what is going on?

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:30.220
 But if I'm really debugging something like in a loop,

00:11:30.220 --> 00:11:31.620
 I'll use console.log.

00:11:31.620 --> 00:11:34.060
 So it comes in, console.log comes out.

00:11:34.060 --> 00:11:35.020
 It says alert.

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:35.860
 I clicked on it.

00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:37.140
 So you don't see that.

00:11:37.140 --> 00:11:39.620
 The second log comes out and away you go.

00:11:39.620 --> 00:11:42.260
 And so this, this is a better debugging mechanism.

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:44.180
 And if you look at systems that I've built,

00:11:44.180 --> 00:11:46.220
 when I have a really complex JavaScript,

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:49.500
 I will sometimes leave console.log statements in it.

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:51.580
 So if you use Sakai

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:53.700
 and you're at a school that uses Sakai

00:11:53.700 --> 00:11:55.140
 and you do console.log,

00:11:55.140 --> 00:11:58.020
 you will see error messages in your production system

00:11:58.020 --> 00:12:00.500
 that I left in there because of the parts of the code

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:03.620
 that were so, the JavaScript was so tricky.

00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:05.460
 I'm like, I wanna be able to talk to you

00:12:05.460 --> 00:12:06.940
 if your stuff breaks.

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:10.740
 And I want any developer to be able to pop this window open

00:12:10.740 --> 00:12:13.140
 and get a clue as to why some of the JavaScript stuff

00:12:13.140 --> 00:12:14.380
 is breaking, 'cause there's just so much

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:15.980
 complex JavaScript in it.

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:19.060
 And so I leave a few little debugging clues.

00:12:19.060 --> 00:12:21.060
 And if you go into the auto grader,

00:12:21.060 --> 00:12:23.180
 you can watch this.

00:12:23.180 --> 00:12:26.580
 I just like debugging and it's sort of not all that costly.

00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:27.700
 I don't put a ton of them in

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:30.340
 'cause then it looks a little sloppy.

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:33.780
 But yeah, I do put a few console logs in.

00:12:33.780 --> 00:12:38.180
 So you can use a debugger.

00:12:38.180 --> 00:12:39.420
 It's a full featured debugger.

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:41.460
 You can view the source, you can inspect.

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:43.260
 You probably by now have figured out

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:44.420
 how to inspect elements.

00:12:44.420 --> 00:12:45.340
 So you can look through the,

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:46.460
 and what you're looking through there

00:12:46.460 --> 00:12:48.220
 is the document object model.

00:12:48.220 --> 00:12:50.900
 But they also have the full feature debugger

00:12:50.900 --> 00:12:53.500
 where if you're looking in the source code,

00:12:53.500 --> 00:12:56.340
 you can go on to the line that you're interested in

00:12:56.340 --> 00:13:00.700
 and click, and then that will set a break point.

00:13:00.700 --> 00:13:01.940
 And what you, but it doesn't,

00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:04.300
 but usually the code's already executed.

00:13:04.300 --> 00:13:06.660
 So you have to set the break point,

00:13:06.660 --> 00:13:07.780
 then you got to refresh the page,

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:09.380
 and it remembers where you set the break point,

00:13:09.380 --> 00:13:10.980
 and then it stops it.

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:13.660
 Okay, and so you kind of set the break point

00:13:13.660 --> 00:13:16.260
 and then hit refresh, you'll figure it out.

00:13:16.260 --> 00:13:19.300
 Because by the time it's all done,

00:13:19.300 --> 00:13:20.780
 it can't go back in time.

00:13:20.780 --> 00:13:23.300
 It's past that line, so you have to see the line,

00:13:23.300 --> 00:13:25.420
 set the break point, refresh the page,

00:13:25.420 --> 00:13:28.860
 then it knows to break point, catch the break point

00:13:28.860 --> 00:13:32.540
 as it's going by rather than going back in time

00:13:32.540 --> 00:13:34.140
 'cause it doesn't remember.

00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:36.540
 It can't run time backwards, just forwards.

00:13:36.540 --> 00:13:40.980
 So that gives you a little sense of what it is like

00:13:40.980 --> 00:13:43.420
 to do JavaScript in the browser.

00:13:43.420 --> 00:13:45.660
 And now we're gonna just look at JavaScript

00:13:45.660 --> 00:13:47.740
 as if it were a regular programming language.

00:13:47.740 --> 00:13:49.980
 And this applies whether it's in the browser,

00:13:49.980 --> 00:13:52.460
 in the server, in Vue, or whatever.

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:55.040
 (upbeat music)

